<DOC><DOCNO> AP880323-0245 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-23-88 0734EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv25   03-23 0612</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 25,0637</SECOND><NOTE>$adv25</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 25 and Thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mainline churches _ Protestant, Roman Catholicand Eastern Orthodox _ have a long-time policy against endorsing oropposing specific political candidates seeking election.   But the United Church of Christ decided last week that the ruledoesn't apply to nominees for appointed public offices such as theU.S. Supreme Court.   The 1.7-million-member denomination's executive council approvedspeaking out on such appointed candidates after hearing a studyreport that neither the Bible, the U.S. Constitution nor IRSregulations forbid it.   Some religious leaders, including the denomination's president,the Rev. Avery Post, had opposed the nomination last year of JudgeRobert Bork to the high court, while others supported him. Heeventually withdrew.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Termed the first such direct shipment from thiscountry to the Soviet Union, two tons of kosher food and otherPassover supplies were sent by Manhattan's Park East Synagogue tothe Chorale Synagogue in Moscow.   Rabbi Arthur Schneier, leader of the Manhattan synagogue andpresident of the Appeal of Concience Foundation, worked out plansfor the shipment with Soviet officials in January. Passover week isApril 2-9.</TEXT><DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Nebraska pastor told students atSouthern Baptist Theological Seminary that preachers need to domore story-telling in their sermons.   ``Stories are life changers,'' said the Rev. Calvin Miller ofOmaha. ``They produce and their product is real.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bishop Herbert Chilstrom, head of theEvangelical Lutheran Church in America, told a meeting ofpresidents of Lutheran Colleges:   ``The first thing you can expect from the church is money. Thesecond thing you can expect is not much of it.''   There are 52 Lutheran colleges in the country.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A delegation of Protestant and Roman Catholicleaders from Mozambique, which suffers from drought, hunger andbrutal civil strife, has appealed to Americans for relief anddevelopment aid.   ``Anything withheld for political or ideological motives simplymeans we are allowing people to die in front of us just because weare unsure of their political preferences,'' the churchmen said.   They said an estimated 4.5 million people in Mozambique arethreatened by starvation, that about 100,000 have been killed byroving anti-government ``bandidos'' and more than 2 million peopledisplaced as refugees.</TEXT><DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Methodist Commission on Religionand Race says that a nationwide movement to make English theofficial language of the United States is a ``new form of racism''   The Rev. Yolanda Pupo-Ortiz, a commission staff member, saidthat on the surface the ``English only'' movement appears harmless,but ``its real purpose is to make a legal base for discrimination.''   Proponents of the movement contend that multilingualismperpetuates divisions. Thirty-two states have introducedconstitutional amendments to recognize English as their officiallanguage.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Churches can be ``effective partners'' inhelping the poor, but ``we cannot go it alone,'' says AuxiliaryBishop John H. Ricard of Baltimore.   Testifying recently for the U.S. Catholic Conference before aHouse subcommittee, he said churches and other private groups havelabored valiantly to take up the slack caused by erosion ofgovernment programs.   But he said the private sector can't substitute for the``essential responsibility'' of the government.   Increased church efforts, he said, are ``a desperate attempt tofeed hungry people when others have abandoned theirresponsibility,'' but ``we cannot pretend that soup kitchens andshelters'' are sufficient.   ``They cannot substitute for a national commitment to end hungerand invest our common resources to feed the hungry,'' he added.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, March 25</NOTE></DOC>